hints_latex:
Recall that the \textbf{Lagrange Remainder formula} gives that the
remainder (error) in the \emph{k}-th degree Taylor polynomial of
\emph{f} at \emph{a} is:

\begin{align*}
R_k(x) = \frac{f^{(k+1)}(c)}{(k+1)!} (x-a)^{k+1}
\end{align*}

where $\displaystyle c$ is some (undetermined) number in the interval
$\displaystyle [a, x]$.

Since we are using a \emph{first-degree} \textbf{Maclaurin polynomial},
$a = 0$ and $k = 1$:

\begin{align*}
R_1(x)=\frac{f''(c)}{2!} x^2
\end{align*}

for some $\displaystyle c$ in the interval $\displaystyle [0, x]$.

sols_latex:
To apply the Lagrange Remainder Formula, we first need to find an $x$
such that
$\displaystyle f(x) = \ln(1-x^2) = \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right)$, that
is,
$\displaystyle 1-x^2 = \frac{8}{9} \Leftrightarrow x = \pm \frac{1}{3}$.

Since $\displaystyle \ln(1-x^2)$ is an even function, we choose the
positive root $\displaystyle x = \frac{1}{3}$ without loss of
generality.

By Taylor's Remainder theorem (as applied to Maclaurin polynomials),

\begin{align*}
T_1(x) + \text{min}\{R_{1}(x)\} \leq f(x) \leq T_1(x) +  \text{max}\{R_{1}(x)\}
\end{align*}

where $\displaystyle \text{min}\{R_{1}(x)\}$ and
$\displaystyle \text{max}\{R_{1}(x)\}$ denote the minimum and maximum
values of $\displaystyle R_{1}(x)$ on the interval
$\displaystyle [0, x]$, respectively.

Since we know that $\displaystyle T_1(x) = 0$ from
{part
(a)}, we simply consider:

\begin{align*}
\text{min}\{R_{1}(x)\} \leq \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right) \leq \text{max}\{R_{1}(x)\}
\end{align*}

We now calculate the upper and lower bounds of the error. To do so, we
substitute $\displaystyle x = \frac{1}{3}$ into the Lagrange Remainder
Formula:

\begin{align*}
R_1\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)=\frac{f''(c)}{2!} \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 = \frac{f''(c)}{18}
\end{align*}

for some $c$ in in the interval $[0, \frac{1}{3}]$. To find the error
bounds, we maximize this function as a function of $c$. But observe that

\begin{align*}
f''(x) = \frac{-2(x^2+1)}{(1-x^2)^2}
\end{align*}

is monotonically decreasing on the interval $[0, \frac{1}{3}]$ (the
denominator is increasing while the numerator is decreasing (note the
minus sign), so overall $\displaystyle f''(x)$ is decreasing). Hence the
minimum and maximum values of the error are attained at
$c = \frac{1}{3}$ and $\displaystyle c = 0$, respectively.

Plugging this in we obtain the required lower and upper bound for the
error:

\begin{align*}
\frac{f''(\frac{1}{3})}{18} &\leq \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right) \leq \frac{f''(0)}{18} \\
\frac{1}{18} \cdot \frac{-2((\frac{1}{3})^2 + 1)}{(1-(\frac{1}{3})^2)^2} &\leq \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right) \leq \frac{1}{18} \cdot \frac{-2(0^2 + 1)}{(1-0^2)^2} \\
\frac{1}{18} \cdot \frac{-180}{64} &\leq \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right) \leq \frac1{18} \cdot -2 \\
{ \color{blue} -\frac5{32} } \, &{ \color{blue} \leq \ln\left(\frac{8}{9}\right) \leq -\frac19}
\end{align*}
